In \cite{TakaSolid}, N. Ozawa introduced the notion of \emph{solid} von Neumann algebras. It is easy to check that in the $\mathrm{II}_1$ case, the definition of solidity given in \cite{TakaSolid} is equivalent to the following one (see Proposition \ref{formulation}). 
\begin{defs}
Let $M$ be a von Neumann algebra. We say that $M$ is \emph{solid} if for every subalgebra with expectation $Q \subset M$ there exist projections $z_n \in \mathcal{Z}(Q)$ with $\sum_n z_n=1$ such that $Qz_0$ is amenable and $Qz_n$ is a non-amenable factor for all $n \geq 1$.
\end{defs}

In this section, we are interested in a \emph{relative} version of solidity :

\begin{defs}
Let $M$ be a von Neumann algebra and $N \subset M$ a subalgebra with expectation. We say that $M$ is \emph{solid relatively to} $N$ if for every subalgebra with expectation $Q \subset 1_QM1_Q$ such that $Q \nprec_M N$ there exist projections $z_n \in \mathcal{Z}(Q)$ with $\sum_n z_n=1_Q$ such that $Qz_0$ is amenable and $Qz_n$ is a non-amenable factor for all $n \geq 1$.
\end{defs}

Clearly, a von Neumann algebra $M$ is solid if and only if it is solid relatively to $\mathbb{C}$. The following property justifies the terminology.
\begin{prop} \label{relative_absolute}
Let $M$ be a von Neumann algebra and $N \subset M$ a subalgebra with expectation. If $M$ is solid relatively to $N$ and $N$ is solid then $M$ is solid.
\end{prop}
\begin{proof} If $M$ is not solid then there exists a subalgebra with expectation $Q \subset 1_QM1_Q$ with diffuse center such that $Q$ is properly non-amenable. Thus by relative solidity we must have $Q \prec_M N$. Hence there exist a non-zero projection $p \in Q$ and a subalgebra with expectation $C \subset 1_CN1_C$ such that $pQp \sim_M C$. Thus $C$ is also non-amenable and has diffuse center. This contradicts the solidity of $N$. 
\end{proof}

